{"title_page": "Deputy Prime Minister of Malaysia", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Short description|Second highest political office in Malaysia}}\n{{Infobox official post\n| post                    = Deputy Prime Minister\n| body                    = Malaysia\n| native_name             = ''Timbalan Perdana Menteri Malaysia''\n| insignia                = Coat of arms of Malaysia.svg\n| insigniasize            =\n| insigniacaption         =\n| flag                    = \n| flagsize                = 130px\n| flagcaption             = <small>Official emblem of the Office of the Prime Minister</small>\n| incumbent               = Defunct\n| image                   = \n| imagesize               = 150px\n| incumbentsince          = 10 March 2020\n| department              = [[Prime Minister's Department|Deputy Prime Minister's Office]]\n| style                   = [[Malay titles|Yang Amat Berhormat]] <small>(The Most Honourable)</small>\n| member_of               = [[Cabinet of Malaysia|Cabinet]]\n| reports_to              = [[Parliament of Malaysia|Parliament]]\n| seat                    = [[Perdana Putra]], [[Putrajaya]]\n| residence               = Seri Satria\n| nominator               = [[Prime Minister of Malaysia|Prime Minister]]\n| appointer               = [[Yang di-Pertuan Agong]]\n| appointer_qualified     =\n| termlength              = 5 years, renewable. Depended on the Prime Minister\n| constituting_instrument =\n| formation               = {{start date and years ago|df=yes|1957|08|31}}\n| inaugural               = [[Tun Abdul Razak]]\n| salary                  = [[Malaysian ringgit|MYR]]18,168.15 monthly<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cpps.org.my/images/articles/Fact%20Sheet%20Remuneration%20of%20Elected%20Officials%20in%20Malaysia.pdf|title=CPPS Policy Factsheet: Remuneration of Elected Officials in Malaysia|publisher=Centre for Public Policy Studies|accessdate=11 May 2016|format=PDF|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511013733/http://cpps.org.my/images/articles/Fact%20Sheet%20Remuneration%20of%20Elected%20Officials%20in%20Malaysia.pdf|archivedate=11 May 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| website                 = {{URL|http://www.pmo.gov.my/tpm/|www.pmo.gov.my/tpm}}\n}}\n{{Politics of Malaysia}}\n\nThe '''Deputy Prime Minister of Malaysia''' ({{lang-ms|Timbalan Perdana Menteri Malaysia}}) is the second highest political office in [[Malaysia]]. There have been twelve deputy prime ministers since the office was created in 1957. The first [[Prime Minister of Malaysia]], [[Tunku Abdul Rahman]], started the convention of appointing a Deputy Prime Minister.\n\nThe latest former Deputy Prime Minister is [[Wan Azizah Wan Ismail]], in office from 10 May 2018 until 24 February 2020, is the first female to hold the Deputy Prime Minister position.\n\n== Deputy Prime Minister appointment ==\n{{see also|List of United Malays National Organisation leaders}}\nAlthough Malaysia has always had a Deputy Prime Minister since independence, a Prime Minister may choose not to appoint a Deputy Prime Minister. The office of Deputy Prime Minister is not provided for in the [[Constitution of Malaysia]]. At the same time, a Prime Minister could appoint more than one Deputy Prime Minister, as has occurred before in Singapore.\n\nBy the practice of the past ruling coalition [[Barisan Nasional]], where the [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) was the unofficial leader, the UMNO Deputy President was usually appointed the Deputy Prime Minister by the Prime Minister (who was the UMNO President). In the organisational structure of Barisan Nasional, the President and Deputy President of UMNO were automatically made the Chairman and Deputy Chairman of Barisan Nasional.\n\nFrom 21 May 2018 until 24 February 2020,the ruling coalition - Pakatan Harapan, a coalition of four equal partner parties, the holder of the position of Deputy Prime Minister was decided upon by the coalition's Presidential Council. The postholder was Datuk Seri Dr Wan Azizah binti Wan Ismail, who was the first female holder of post.\n\n== Deaths, resignations and removals from office ==\nOf the twelve previous officeholders, five have gone on to become prime minister. Of the remaining, one died in office, three resigned, two were removed from office by the sitting prime minister, and one disqualified from office due to lost in [[2018 Malaysian general election|14th General Election]].\n\n[[Ismail Abdul Rahman]] died in office due to massive heart attack in 1973. [[Musa Hitam]] resigned from [[second Mahathir cabinet]] over differences with Prime Minister over government policy in 1986. [[Ghafar Baba]] resigned from his portfolio following UMNO grassroots lost confidence in his leadership and his position as Deputy President of UMNO was challenged by Anwar Ibrahim in the UMNO's top leadership election. [[Anwar Ibrahim]] was the first deputy prime minister to be sacked after being accused and subsequently charged with corruption and sodomy in 1998. [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] was the second DPM to be removed from office after being dropped from the Cabinet by Prime Minister [[Najib Razak]] in a reshuffle in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utusan.com.my/berita/politik/muhyiddin-terima-penggugurannya-dengan-hati-terbuka-1.117967|title=Muhyiddin terima penggugurannya dengan hati terbuka|language=Malay|publisher=Utusan Malaysia|date=28 July 2015|accessdate=11 May 2016}}</ref> He later was sacked from his party.<ref> {{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/umno-sacks-former-malaysian-dpm-muhyiddin-yassin-and-mukhriz-mah-7958782|title=UMNO sacks former Malaysian DPM Muhyiddin Yassin and Mukhriz Mahathir|publisher=Channel NewsAsia|date=24 June 2018|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> [[Wan Azizah Wan Ismail]] resigned after the [[seventh Mahathir cabinet]] was dissolved in 2020.\n\n== List of Deputy Prime Ministers of Malaysia ==\n'''Colour key''' (for political parties):<br />\n{{legend